The Federal Reserve is deeply insolvent. But it's not a problem....until it is üö®

When a company makes losses which wipe out its capital and reserves, it is said to be "insolvent".  The same thing applies when its assets have declined in value by more than its capital and reserves (unrealized losses).  

When you are insolvent it's generally time to call in the receivers.     

Many banks around the world are facing losses on the bonds they bought when interest rates were close to zero.  As interest rates rose, those bonds fell in price.  A 2% bond is worth less than a new 5% bond.    

That's exactly what happened to Silicon Valley Bank. They bought a bunch of low-yielding bond. Then interest rates rose, causing the price of those bonds to fall.
